ractText>&lt;p>CEO compensation packages have been a focus of much academic and media interest.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; One important question is whether corporate governance mechanisms can play a significant role in determining the level and structure of executive compensation.&amp;nbsp;The literature suggests that corporate governance mechanisms may help to reduce the agency conflicts between executives and shareholders, and hence have an impact on compensation policy.&amp;nbsp;Those mechanisms include ownership and board structure of companies.&amp;nbsp;In this paper the aim is to investigate whether corporate governance mechanisms have an impact on the level of CEO compensation for a sample of quoted UK companies from 1997 to 2004.&amp;nbsp; In particular,&amp;nbsp;the&amp;nbsp;study will examine whether institutional shareholders influence the level of executive compensation and pay-performance sensitivity.&amp;nbsp;Additionally, the role of managerial shareholdings, and the board structure of companies are also examined.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p> 
&lt;p>This study will contribute to the literature by examining the role of a comprehensive set of corporate governance variables in determining the structure of CEO compensation.&amp;nbsp;It will be also the first study that explores the impact of corporate governance mechanisms on the level of CEO compensation and the pay for performance sensitivity for the UK companies.&amp;nbsp; In the empirical analysis, I&amp;nbsp;this study will&amp;nbsp;employ panel data estimation technique.&lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2007-05-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2006-06-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>47220</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>E2DF83A6-90B9-4808-9499-44F671F5F4B5</gtr:id><gtr:title>CEO Compensation and Firm Performance: an Empirical Investigation of UK Panel Data</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>European Financial Management</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/408e8a8d9cb1c61122c6205ac6c8c947"><gtr:id>408e8a8d9cb1c61122c6205ac6c8c947</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Ozkan N</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2011-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>doi_53cfa4fa40341e08</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>E7B7BE25-6822-44BE-A31D-8075A978260E</gtr:id><gtr:title>Do corporate governance mec